Phase 1 should be a pure preparatory refactor: expose validation as named structure, flatten the nested conditional, and keep `acceptRow` returning `boolean` with identical success/failure behavior and the same push side effect only on success. The review boundary is: no contract change, no new rejection semantics, and existing green tests stay logically unchanged.

A good phase-1 patch shape is:

```ts
type RowKind = "person" | "company";
type RowStatus = "active" | "inactive";
type AcceptedRow = {
  id: string;
  kind: RowKind;
  score: number;
  status: RowStatus;
};

type RawAcceptedRow = [id: string, kind: RowKind, scoreText: string, status: RowStatus];

function isAcceptedRow(row: string[]): row is RawAcceptedRow {
  if (row.length !== 4) return false;

  const [id, kind, scoreText, status] = row;

  if (id === "") return false;
  if (kind !== "person" && kind !== "company") return false;
  if (!/^\d+$/.test(scoreText)) return false;
  if (status !== "active" && status !== "inactive") return false;

  return true;
}

function toAcceptedRow([id, kind, scoreText, status]: RawAcceptedRow): AcceptedRow {
  return {
    id,
    kind,
    score: Number(scoreText),
    status,
  };
}

export function acceptRow(row: string[]): boolean {
  if (!isAcceptedRow(row)) return false;

  acceptedRows.push(toAcceptedRow(row));
  return true;
}
```

Why this is the right preparatory cut:
- Validation is now explicit and isolated.
- Data meaning is named instead of encoded in `row[0]`, `row[1]`, etc.
- The boolean contract and observable behavior are preserved.
- The later feature can change only the validation result shape without reworking mutation or parsing again.

Phase 2 should introduce the new contract and only then change tests to assert typed rejection reasons. Keep the validation order explicit so rejection precedence stays deliberate: `field-count`, then `missing-id`, then `kind`, then `score`, then `status`.

A good phase-2 patch shape is:

```ts
type RowKind = "person" | "company";
type RowStatus = "active" | "inactive";

type AcceptedRow = {
  id: string;
  kind: RowKind;
  score: number;
  status: RowStatus;
};

type AcceptanceResult =
  | { accepted: true }
  | {
      accepted: false;
      reason: "field-count" | "missing-id" | "kind" | "score" | "status";
    };

type ValidationResult =
  | { ok: true; value: AcceptedRow }
  | {
      ok: false;
      reason: "field-count" | "missing-id" | "kind" | "score" | "status";
    };

function validateRow(row: string[]): ValidationResult {
  if (row.length !== 4) {
    return { ok: false, reason: "field-count" };
  }

  const [id, kind, scoreText, status] = row;

  if (id === "") {
    return { ok: false, reason: "missing-id" };
  }

  if (kind !== "person" && kind !== "company") {
    return { ok: false, reason: "kind" };
  }

  if (!/^\d+$/.test(scoreText)) {
    return { ok: false, reason: "score" };
  }

  if (status !== "active" && status !== "inactive") {
    return { ok: false, reason: "status" };
  }

  return {
    ok: true,
    value: {
      id,
      kind,
      score: Number(scoreText),
      status,
    },
  };
}

export function acceptRow(row: string[]): AcceptanceResult {
  const validation = validateRow(row);

  if (!validation.ok) {
    return { accepted: false, reason: validation.reason };
  }

  acceptedRows.push(validation.value);
  return { accepted: true };
}
```

Test plan:
- Phase 1: keep existing tests passing without changing expected behavior.
- Phase 2: update the success test to expect `{ accepted: true }` and add one rejection test per reason.
- For each rejection case, also assert that no row was pushed.

Minimal rejection matrix:

```ts
expect(acceptRow(["1", "person", "10"]))
  .toEqual({ accepted: false, reason: "field-count" });

expect(acceptRow(["", "person", "10", "active"]))
  .toEqual({ accepted: false, reason: "missing-id" });

expect(acceptRow(["1", "animal", "10", "active"]))
  .toEqual({ accepted: false, reason: "kind" });

expect(acceptRow(["1", "person", "10x", "active"]))
  .toEqual({ accepted: false, reason: "score" });

expect(acceptRow(["1", "person", "10", "pending"]))
  .toEqual({ accepted: false, reason: "status" });
```

That keeps the two intents reviewable:
1. preparatory refactoring only
2. contract change plus new rejection semantics and tests
